ith the complex registers of bodily subjectivity — violence, wonder, and laughter — to profoundly contest categories of oppression and resistance, autonomy and subjection, and state and civil society that marked the social theory of the late twentieth century. This provocative book will surely attract attention with its signal contribution to the rich interdisciplinary arena of scholarship on colonial and postcolonial discourse, history, anthropology, philosophy, political science, psychoanalysis, and literary criticism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aPostcolonialismzAfrica. 0aPower (Social sciences)zAfrica. 0aSubjectivity. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aacademic.  aafrica.  aafricanist.  aanthropology.  aautonomy.  acolonial.  acolonialism.  acontemporary africa.  acontemporary.  aessay collection.  ainterdisciplinary.  aliterary criticism.  aliterary theory.  amodern world.  anativist.  aoppression.  aphilosophy.  apolitical science.  apostcolonial studies.  apostcolonial theory.  apostcolonial.  apower.  apsychoanalysis.  aresistance.  ascholarly.  asubjection.  asubjectivity.  atheoretical.  aviolence.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052020434840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091753840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520917538423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520917538/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY